            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marat Volkova\u2019s story begins not with the gray concrete of a Soviet city, but with the winds sweeping across Siberia\u2019s Lake Baikal. Born to a Buryat historian mother and a Russian physicist father, his upbringing was a blend of ancient folklore and empirical data. The name \u201cMarat\u201d was an intellectual choice by his parents; the surname \u201cVolkova\u201d was his mother\u2019s, a quiet matriarchal statement. In 1991, with the Soviet Union collapsing, his family emigrated, trading the vastness of Siberia for the dense, foggy avenues of San Francisco's Richmond District.\n\nHis initial years in America were a study in dissonance. He found solace not in sports but on the high school debate team, where he learned to structure arguments and wield facts like weapons. This led him to UC Berkeley\u2019s Graduate School of Journalism, where he initially pursued traditional investigative reporting. The key turning point came during a post-graduation internship in the early 2000s, where he watched the newspaper industry hemorrhage money and influence. He saw the future wasn\u2019t just in words, but in the patterns hiding within raw information. He spent his nights teaching himself to code, merging his journalistic ethics with the rigid logic of programming.\n\nNow 44, Marat is the lead data journalist for a prominent online news organization headquartered in SoMa. His daily 1.8-mile commute from his minimalist Hayes Valley apartment is a ritual of observation, absorbing the city's rhythm via the Muni Metro. He leads a team that builds visualizations and uncovers stories about housing disparities and climate change from vast, impersonal datasets.\n\nHis personal life is one of curated calm. A brief, intense marriage in his late twenties fizzled under the weight of his career focus, teaching him the value of balance. He is now in a stable, seven-year relationship with a landscape architect who appreciates his quiet intensity. Marat\u2019s greatest hope isn't a Pulitzer, but to author a definitive book\u2014one that translates the cold data of systemic inequality into a powerful human narrative his mother would have understood. He seeks not just to inform, but to reveal the elegant, often heartbreaking, truth hidden in the numbers."
