            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe is eight years old, standing on the shore of a frozen Lake Baikal. His mother, pointing to the deep, crystalline fissures in the ice, doesn\u2019t speak of physics but of sleeping spirits. She tells him patterns are the earth\u2019s oldest language. He feels a profound sense of awe, not just for the folklore, but for the immense, visible data of the ice itself. This moment fused storytelling with observation, setting the foundation for his life\u2019s work of finding the narrative within the pattern. This was in 1988, three years before leaving home forever.\n\n2.\nHis first autumn in the Richmond District, age 12. The relentless fog felt like a physical weight, erasing the Siberian sky from his memory. He stood on a corner on Geary Boulevard, unable to understand the overlapping conversations, the hiss of a Muni bus, the smell of damp eucalyptus. The feeling was not sadness, but a clinical alienation. This profound sense of being outside the system forced him to become its keenest observer, learning to decode the city\u2019s rhythms and rules as a matter of survival, a skill he would later call journalism.\n\n3.\nIt\u2019s 2003, in a dying newsroom that smelled of stale coffee and defeat. He watches a veteran editor stare at a spreadsheet of plummeting circulation numbers with utter despair. But Marat sees something else: a story. In the stark, unforgiving columns of data, he saw a powerful, objective truth that no article could convey. The emotional impact was one of electrifying clarity. This moment pivoted his entire career, convincing him that the future wasn\u2019t just writing the story, but coding the machine that could find it.\n\n4.\nThe quiet in their Hayes Valley apartment after his wife left was the loudest thing he\u2019d ever heard. He was 29. She hadn\u2019t yelled, but had stated with devastating calm, \u201cI can\u2019t compete with a dataset, Marat.\u201d He remembers staring at his screen, lines of Python blurring. The emotional impact was a hollow scoop in his chest, a recognition of his own profound imbalance. That failure taught him that human connection couldn't be quantified or optimized, a hard-learned lesson that made his current, stable relationship possible.\n\n5.\nRiding the N-Judah underground last year, he was reviewing a map visualizing eviction data. Suddenly, the glowing red dots weren't abstract points; they were the faces of families, the fog of the Richmond, the feeling of displacement he himself knew. He felt a powerful, almost heartbreaking surge of empathy, a connection between his code and his own history. It was the moment his life\u2019s ambition crystallized: he wouldn\u2019t just show the data, he would write the book that made everyone else feel what he felt in that instant."
